{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205696398/1930110701/0587.xml":{"full_text":"38\nI BIRTHS, MARRIAGES AND DEATHS\nK.\nMRS. ALMA K. CROSBY\nltrs. Alma M. Crosby, 39. prom\ninent In social circles here, died\nyesterday following a lingering\nillness at her home, 1334 Hem\nlock St. N. W.\nMrs. Crosby, who was the wife\nof Major George J. Crosby, re\ntired officer of the United States\nArmy and general manager of\nthe Stelos Co., was a native of\nWashington. The second woman\nto enlist in the Marine Corps\nwhen this country entered the\nwar, she served as a \u201cMarinette\u201d\nat Marine headquarters here from\nAugust, 1914, to July, 1919. Prom\n1919 to 1922 she served in the\nMarine Reserves.\nMajor and Mrs. Crosby were\nmarried in 1928 shortly after\nMajor Crosby\u2019s retirement. Enter\ning the Army in 1900, Major\nCrosby saw active service in\nFrance and was adjutant of the\nTank Corps in the A. E. P. Dur\ning the Wilson and Harding ad\nministrations, he was consul at\nfour different posts in Canada.\nMrs. Crbeby is survived by her\nhusband and her parents, Mr.\nand Mrs. J. Bernard Colclazer, of\nJ 319 Allison St. N. W.\nFuneral services will be held on\nMonday at her residence, with\nburial following In Arlington Na\n.tional Cemetery accompanied by\nfull military honors.\nJULIAN ENCISO\nDr. Julian Enciso, Argentine\ncharge died on Wed\nnesday aboard the 8. 8. Western\nPrince on which he was sailing\nto Buenos Aires, according to\nword received here yesterday.\nDr. Enciso, who had been ailing\nfor several weeks, left Washing\nton October 24 for home, where\nhe was to receive medical treat\nment.\nComing to Washington in 1928\nas counsellor of the Argentine\nembassy, he became charge d\u2019af\nfaires shortly after in that same\nyear and retained that position\nuntil the last month, when his\nill health forced him to aban\ndon it.\nBefore coming here, *Dr. Enciso\nhad served as secretary to Argen\ntine legations in Madrid, Berlin,\nSantiago, Chile, Berne and Rio\nde Janeiro. He had been charge\nd'affaires at Copenhagen, and he\nwas also delegated by his coun\ntry to observe at the League of\n\"Nations.\nHe is survived by his widow,\nMrs. Susana Ugalde Enciso.\nMRS. LEE R. GROESBECK\nFuneral services for Mrs. Lee\nRobinson Groesbeck, wife of Ed\nward C. Groesbeck, a metallurgist\nof the United States Bureau of\nStandards, who died yesterday,\nwill be held tomorrow at 11 a. m.\nfrom the residence of her brother,\nCharles A. Robinson, 3511 Wood\nley Rd. The services will be con\nducted by Dr. John T. Ensor, of\nBaltimore, who will be assisted by\nDr. Charles Wood, former pastor\nof the Church of the Covenant, of\nwhich Mrs. Groesbeck was a mem\nber.\nA native of Baltimore, the\ndaughter of the late Charles A.\nRobinson and Alice Hodges Robin\nson, she was an alumna of\nGoucher College and the Peabody\nConservatory of Music.\nSurviving her are her husband,\nI her brother, and three sister, Mrs.\nEmory L. Stinchcomb. of Balti\nmore; Mrs. J. Phelps Hand and\nMiss Mary V. Robinson, of Wash\nington.\nJOHN C. FLOYD\nJohn Charles Floyd, 72, Demo\ncratic representative from Ar\nkansas from 1905 to 1915, died\nyesterday at his home in Yell\nville, Ark., according to word re\nceived here today.\nBorn in Sparta, Tenn., he moved\nto Benton county, Ark., with his\nparents when a child. He gradu\nated from the University of Ar\nkansas in 1879 and practiced\nlaw for 10 years. Following his\nterm in Congress, he returned\nto Yellville to practice law. Later\nhe was elected prosecuting attor\nney for the fourteenth judicial\ncircuit. In 1912 he was one of\nthe managers appointed by the\nHouse to conduct the impeach\nment proceedings brought against\nRobert W. Archibald? judge of\nthe United States Commerce\nCourt,\nCHAUNCEY EDGAR TRAINOR\nFuneral services for Chauncey\nEdgar Trainor, 62, patent attorney,\nwho died on Wednesday follow\ning a sudden illness at the resi\ndence of his daughter, Mrs. John\nDriscoll, 227 Upshur St. N. W.,\nwere held today from the funeral\nparlors of V. L. Speare Co., 1009\nH St. N. W. Burial was in Cedar\nHill Cemetery.\nMr. Trainor, who was bom in\nPoseyville, Ind., was connected\nwith a law firm here for 13\nyears and at the time' of his\ndeath was connected with a New\nYork firm which maintains\noffices here.\nHe is survived by his widow,\nMrs. Susie Trainor, of Woodside,\nMd., and a daughter, Mrs. Dris\ncoll.\nMRS. LOTTIE B. SPRINGS\nMrs. Lottie B. Springs, 80, of\nthe Conard Apartments, Thir\nteenth and I Streets Northwest,\ndied yesterday in Emergency Hos\npital of bronchial pneumonia,\nwhich physicians say, developed\nfrom injuries she suffered when\nshe fell over her cane on Friday\nin the Colorado Building.\nWhen Coroner J. Ramsay\nNevitt learned that the woman\nhad suffered a fractured hip from\nher 1 fall and that heart trouble\nand pneumonia had resulted, he\nissued a Certificate of accidental\ndeath.\nDEATHS\nCROSBY. ALMA M.\u2014Pawed away on\nThursday. November O, 1930, at her\nresidence. 13*M Hemlock Street Northwest,\nALMA M. CROSBY, the beloved wile of\nMajor George J. Crosby. Doited States\nArmy, retired, and the daughter of Mr.\nand Mrs. J Bernard Colclaaer.\nFuneral services will be conducted from\nher late residence. 1324 Hemlock Street\nNorthwest on Monday morning. November\n10. 1930. at 8:15 o\u2019clock, thence to the\nShrine of the Sacred Heart (corner of Six\nteenth Street and Park Road Northwest\nwhere requiem mass will be -aid at 9\no'clock for the repose of her soul. Inter\nment will follow at Arlington -ntinnal\nCemetery. Relatives and friends are in\nvited to attend.\nCROUCH. CHARLIE H.\u2014On Wednesday\nmorning, November 6, 1930. at 4\no'clock, at his residence. 1745 First street\nNorthwest. CHARLIE H. CROUCH, the be\nloved husband of Emeline Crouch, in the\nthirty-second year of his age. Besides\nbis wife, he Is survived by his parents,\nMr. and Mrs. W. H. Crouch: also M.ss\nMargaret Crouch. Mrs. E. L. .ewett. M,s.\nM. L. Moore. Mrs. Lena Scandoios, Mrs.\nW. A, Redfield, of Richmond. Va.; E. L.\nCrouch, of Richmond. Va Miss Ola\nCrouch, George W. Crouch, of Philadel\nphia. Pa., and Ernest F. Crouch.\nFuneral services will be conducted from\nhis late residence on Friday afternoon. No\nvember 7. 1930. at 2 o\u2019clock. Interment\nwill follow at Cellar Hill Cemetery. Rela\ntives and friends are invited to attend.\n(Richmond. Va\u201e papers please coyy.)\nNOVOTNY. FRANK A.\u2014Suddenly. on\nThursday morning. November 6. .IMO,\nat tl o'clock, at 1112 H Street Nirtheast.\nFRANK A. NOVOTNY. He is survived\nby hie wife, father, mother and two sis\nters. Mrs. Carrey and Mrs. Reith, of .020\nThird Street Northeast.\nFuneral services will be conducted irom\nhis late residence. 1842 Park Road North\nwest. on Saturday afternoon. November\n8. 1930. at 1:30 o\u2019clgck. Remains rest\ning at Hanlon\u2019s funeral home, 841 H\nStreet Northeast, until Saturday morning,\nNovember 8. 1930. thence to his late resi\ndence. Interment will follow at Fort Lin\ncoln Cemetery.\nFLORISTS\nAPPROPRIATE Funera. Tokens\nGude Bros Co.. 1212 F St N W\nJOHN DANNER\nFuneral services for John Dan\nner, 65, a plate printer in the\nBureau of Printing and Engrav\ning, who died yesterday at his\nresidence, 3524 Center St. N. W.,\nwill be held tomorrow at 9 p. m.\nfrom the W. W. Chambers funeral\nparlors.\nMr. Danner, who was bom in\nBoston, Mass., had been a resi\ndent of Washington for the past\n30 years. He was a member of\nthe Sunset Lodge of Odd Fellows.\nHe is survived by his widow,\nMrs. Ella Shaw Danner; two sis\nters, Mrs. Annie Clark and Mrs.\nLizzie Schneider, of Boston, and\nthree brothers, Michael, Frank\nand Charles Danner, also of Bos\nton.\nMICHAEL MAGUIRE\nFuneral services for Michael\nMaguire, 72, who died on Wednes\nday at his residence, 6918 Sixth\nSt. N. W., following a paralytic\nstroke, will be held tomorrow at\n9 a. m. at the Church of the\nNativity. Burial will be in Mount\nOlivet Cemetery.\nMr. Maguire, who was a native\nof Washington, went West when,\nhe was a boy and lived at various\nplaces there for 40 years until\nhe returned to Washington seven\nyears ago with his brother,\nJoseph, with whom he was living\nhere until his death.\nDEATHS\nMargaret Minogue. 87\" years, U. S.\nSoldiers\u2019 Home Hospital.\nAlbert Weisenborn, 83 years, Galllnger\nHospital.\nMary S. Burton, 77 years, 3503 Fif\nteenth St. N. E.\nIsaac W. Burkart, 73 years, Galllnger\nHospital.\nWilliam J. Kerman, 71 years, 027\nEighth St. N. E.\nJohn T. Springmann. 68 years, 122\nSixth St. S. W.\nElizabeth M. Stanley, 61 years, 23\nMilmarson Pl. N. W.\nCharles King. 50 years, Galllnger\nHospital.\nWyman R. Howe. 50 years. 448 La\nmont St. N. W.\nEmma H. Smith. 47 years. 1328\nIngraham St. N. W.\nMary A. Hughes. 46 years. 3323 Mt.\nPleasant St. N. W.\nColeman Hicks. 36 years. 212 Seventh\nSt. S. W.\nCharles F. Brandler. 23 years, Clifton\nTerrace West.\nDorothy B. Kohn. 10 minutes, Walter\nReed General Hospital.\nJennie H. Irving. 61 years, 132 Sea\nton Pl. N. W.\nDavid Randall. 58 years. Home for\nAged and Infirm.\nClaude Carpenter, 45 years. Freed\nmen\u2019s Hospital.\nAnnie Washington, 40 years. Gailin\nger Hospital.\nWilliam Jackson. 39 years. Freed\nmen\u2019s Hospital.\nWillie Simms, 37 years, Freedmen\u2019s\nHospital. a\nKatie Rollins, 35 years, St. Eliza\nbeths Hospital.\nNaomi Butler, 26 years. 2330 Eighth\nSt. N. W.\nFranklin Onley, 2 years. Children's\nHospital.\nDoris Bursey. 1 year, Galllnger Hos\npital.\nJohn Fenicks, 5 months, Galllnger\nHospital.\nBIRTHS\nJoseph P. and Dorothy C. Kohn, girl.\nLester G. and Gertrude Siddall, girl.\nLangley and Gladys Salyers, girl.\nWilliam P. and Hilda Reese, girl.\nWalter J. and Mary E. Conlon, girl.\nJames R. and Lillian Brown, girl.\nEllery F. and Bernadette P. Colvin,\ngirl.\nDaniel W. and Mary E. I lablnett,\nboy.\nGeorge B. and Margaret M. West,\ngirl.\nBenjamin and Naomi Ik Krick, boy.\nFrancis L. and Mary Dunn. ooy.\nBradley B. and Jean Gilman, boy.\nRobert A. and Elizabeth Moyer, boy.\nBurnett H. and Rebecca Ballard, boy.\nWilliam F. and Henrietta L. Burrlss,\nboy.\nDavid W. and Ida E. Burke, toy\nAntonio and Lucia Santini, girl.\nMontague H. and Evelyn Pollard, boy.\nHugh and Geneva Valentine, boy.\nWalter and Amanda Johnson, girl.\nMcKinley and Mary B. Coates, girl.\nMilton and Cecelia Barnes, girl.\nJames and Anna M. Jackson, girl.\nNorman O. and Mary H. Jarvis, girl.\nPowell and Julia Lawson, boy.\nOliver and Cecelia Fair. boy.\nJohn R. and Ola I. Russell, ooy.\nMARRIAGE LICENSES\nB. F. Montgomery, 52, Clarendon, Va.,\nand Janet Parnel. 42, New York city.\nThe Rev. Hpgh Stevenson.\nCarl Rockafellow, 48, Flemington, N.\nJ., -and Olive Legner, 38. Croton, N. J\nThe Rev. William Pierpoint.\nMelciah Washington, 32, and Edna\nDent, 23. Brandywine. Md. The Rev.\nCharles A. De Vaughn.\nRaymond Green, 34, and Asa Pitts,\n33. The Rev. W. Ik Jarvis.\nJohn Wesley Mclntyre, 27, and Mary\nWhite. 24 The Rev. W. D. Jarvis.\nDowie Bi own. 33. and Viola Green.\n23. The Rev. W. Westray.\nInman Harris. 30. and Estella Day.\n30. The ReV Walter A. Gray.\nRudle Lewis, 31. nnd Landonia Lyea\n36. The Rev. W Westray.\nWilson Jackson. 24. and Clarice Wil\nHams. 23. The Rev. Bernard Botts.\nArthur A. Rein, 22. and Rose Katz.\n22. The Rev A. VOlkman.\nTheodore Watson, jr.. 22. and Hei-'i\nDaniel. 18. The Rev. Edward E Rich\nardson.\nCa l Humphries. 23. and Lillian King.\n20 The Rev. W W. Mclntyre.\nRobert L. Callis. 39, and Jessie Phil\nlips. 53 The Rev. J. E. Brigs.\nGilbert Parker. 28. White Plains. N.\nY.. and Marjorie Marshall. 23. Hous\nton. Tsx. Judge R. B. Mattingly.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nLT. COL. JAMES P. HARBESON\nLieut. Col. James P. Harbeson,\nU. S. A., retired, died on Wednes\nday at Flemingsburg, Ky\u201e accord\ning to word received by the War\nDepartment.\nBorn in Louisville, Ky., on De\ncember 17, 1870, he entered West\nPoint in 1890. He was commis\nsioned as second lieutenant in\n1894 and promoted to first lieu\ntenant four years later. In 1901\nhe was appointed captain and\nmajor in 1916. On August 5,\n1917, he was made colonel of the\ninfantry and lieutenant colonel\nin the regular Army in 1918.\nHe was honorably discharged on\nAugust 3, 1919, and retired for\ndisability in line of duty October\n6, 1919.\nColonel Herbeson received the\nSilver Star citation for gallantry\nin action against the insurgent\nforces at the Philippine Islands,\nJune 13, 1899.\nSurviving him is his brother,\nCharles M. Harbeson, of Flem\ningsburg, Ky.\nMRS. IDA E. FICKLING\nMrs. Ida E. Fickllng, 74. widow\nof Dr. Charles H. Fickling, died\nyesterday at her home in Miami,\nFla., following a brief illness, ac\ncording to word received here to\nday.\nThe body will arrive in Wash\ninton on Monday and will remain\nat the home of her son, Frank G.\nFickling, 6432 Eighth St. N. W\u201e un\ntil the funeral arrangements for\nwhich have not yet been made.\nIn Miami, Mrs. Fickling lived\nwith two of her children, W. I.\nFickling and Mrs. L. B. Souther\nland. Besides these Mrs. Fickling\nis survived by W. W. Fickling, oi\nChicago; Mrs. Maude F. Connell\nand Frank G. and Charles H.\nFickling, of this city, and John F.\nFickling, of Detroit, Mich.\nMrs. Fickling, who was a native\nof Washington, moved to Fioiida\nabout five years ago.\nCHARLIE H. CROUCH\nFuneral services for Charlie H.\nCrouch, 32, a carpenter, who died\nWednesday at his residence fol\nlowing a brief illness, were held\ntoday from his residence, 1745\nFirst' St. N. W., with interment\nin Cedar Hill Cemetery.\nHe is survived by his widow,\nMrs. Emeline Crouch; his parents,\nMr. and Mrs. W. H. Crouch; six\nsisters. Miss Margaret Crouch,\nMrs. E. L. Jewett, \u2018Mrs. M. L.\nMoore and Mrs. Lend Scandoios,\nof Washington; Mrs. W. A. Red\nford, of Richmond, Va\u201e and Miss\nOla Crouch, of Philadelphia, and\nthree brothers, Ernest F\u201e of\nWashington; E. L., of Richmond,\nVa., and George W. Crouch, of\nPhiladelphia.\nPREACHESAT ALEXANDRIA\nThe Rev. Ben Lacy, president\nof Union Theological Seminary,\nRichmond, Va., will preach at\nSecond Presbyterian Church,\nAlexandria, Sunday.\nArmy Orders\nLeave of absence is granted to\neach of the following officers:\nCapt. Stanley Y. Yennedy, in\nfantry, four months.\nFirst Lieut. Charles D. McAl\nlister, Air Corps, two months.\nCol. James L. Long, Coast Ar\ntillery Corps, to be retireed,\nCol. Fred W. Bugbee, infantry,\ndetailed as a member of the\nArmy retiring board, Washing\nton, D. C.\nMajor Cyril A. W. Dawson,\nCoast Artillery Corps, to 955th\nCoast Artillery, Duluth, Minn.\nCapt. Glenn D. Hufford, in\nfantry, is detailed as recorder of\nthe Army retiring board Fitz\nsimons General Hospital, Denver,\nColo,\nMajor Paul N. Bowman. Medi\ncal Corps, to Hawaiian Depart\nment.\nMajor Pemier A. Mix. Medical\nCorps, to Fort Clark, Tex.\nCapt. Edwin 4C. Corensen, Medi\ncal Corps, to Hawaii.\nMajor Douglas W. McEnery,\nMedical Corps, to Fort Francis E.\nWarren, Wyo.\nTlMESfHrrald\nCids\nRATES PER LINE PER\nDAY\nCover insertion In both The\nMorning Herald and\nEvening Times\n1 time 23c\n4 times (consecutive) 20c\n7 times (consecutive) 18c\n30 times (consecutive) 17c\nThese rates are for eonseeotive\nInsertions for undlsplav (want)\nads only.\nAll ads are restricted to their\nproper classification and to the\nregular Times-Herald style of type.\nCorrections of errors In '.lassi\nfled ads must he made before the\nsecond Insertion. No allowance will\nbe made for more than one uncor-\nreefed Insertion.\nSituation wanted and clairvoyant\nads accepted on eash oasis only.\nCount six average words to the\nline. An average word has oil i\nletters.\nThe Washington Times and\nHerald are members of the Associa\ntion of Newspaper Classified silver\ntislng Managers, whleh ineludr-f I\nleading newspapers throughout 'he\nrountry and has for one of Its aims\nthe elimination of fraudulent and\nmisleading classified advertising.\nAds ordered for mere than one\nday and stopped before that time\nwill be charged for the actual\nnumber of times the nd appeared,\ncharging the rate earned.\nCorrect rates furnished on ap\nplication.\nThe Washington Times nnd Herald\nas well as every other member of\nthe aMociaflon rndeavors to print\nonlv truthful classified ndvertis\nmente and will appreciate having\nIts attention called tn any adver\ntisement not conforming io the\nhlcheat standards nf honesty.\nCALL DISTRICT 5268\nASK FOR AN An \"AKER.\nCOLLECTION MAM AFTER\nPUBLICATION\nNavy Orders\nComdr. Damon E. Cummings, to\ncommand United States steamship\nSirius.\nComdr. Paul E. Speicher, to com\nmand United States steamship\nLansdale.\nLieut. Comdr. Charles S. Alden,\nto command United States steam\nship Jacob Jones.\nLieut. Comdr. Charles P. Cecil,\nto United States steamship West\nVirginia.\nLieut. Comdr. Volney O. Clark,\nto United States steamship Oglala.\nLieut. Comdr. Ralph U. Hyde, to\naide and flag secretary on staff\ncommander Training Squadron.\nLieut. Comdr. Charles N. Ingra\nham, to command United States\nsteamship Hale.\nLieut. Comdr. Whitley Perkins,\nto command United States steam\nship Crowninshield.\nLieut. Comdr. Lybrand P. Smith,\nto continue duty command United\nStates steamship Claxton.\nLieut. Comdr. Earl E. Stone, to\naide on staff commander in chief\nUnited States fleet, and additional\nduty as fleet communication offi\ncer\u00ab\nLieut. Homer E. Curlee, to\nUnited States steamship Cole, as\nexecutive officer.\nLieut. John K. Lynch, to United\nStates steamship Hamilton.\nLieut. Thomas J. Kelly, to duty\nas resident representative of Naval\nPetroleum Reserves No. 1 and 2,\nTaft Calif.\nLieut. Lester R. Reiter, to United\nStates steamship Cole.\nLieut. James A. Roberts, jr., to\nUnited. States steamship Litch\nfield.\nLieut. Arthur C. Smith, to\nUnited States steamship Salinas.\nLieut. Talbot Smith, to home.\nLieut. (J. G.) John F. Hines, jr.,\nto United States steamship Wil\nliamson.\nLieut. (J. G.) Thomas J. Kimes,\nto United States steamship Ram\napo.\nLieut. (J. G.) Carroll H.Taecker.\nto Asiatic Station.\nEnsign Burrell C. Allen, to Bat\ntleship Division No. 4, Battle Fleet,\nfor communication duty.\nDorothy King, 10,\nReported Missing\nPolice last night were asked to\naid in locating Dorothy King, 10,\nwho has been missing from her\nhome, 322 C St. S. E., since ear\nlier in the day.\nHer father, John H. King, de\nscribed his daughter as having\nblue eyes, light hair and of fair\ncomplexion.\nBuy Now for Better Business\nPromote Purchasing Power\n\nIf every home-owner, store proprietor, and business firm manager will inven\ntory his odd jobs of replacement, renewal and repair, enough work will be dis\ncovered to give immediate employment to every unemployed man and woman\nin Washington,\nThis step would increase at once the purchasing power of persons now un\nemployed. More money would come into circulation; business operations\nwould be speeded up, and local firms would have to hire more employes to\nhandle the resulting increase in business.\nYou can promote community purchasing power and hasten business revival\nby digging up long-deferred jobs of cleaning, redecoration, remodeling and\nrepair and by giving such jobs to unemployed persons now willing and wait\ning for work.\nEach new job which you create helps some worthy person back o nthe road to\nself-support. He then joins with you in the army of buyers whose united pur\nchases are the only sure means of recreating confidence.\nCalvin Coolidge states: \u201cIt is a public duty to buy what you can afford.\u201d\nCreate a new job and enable others to join with you to \u201cBuy Now for Better\nBusiness.\u201d\nBISHOP WILLIAM F. McDOWBLL of\nthe Methodist Episcopal Church\n(South).\nBISHOP JAMES E. FREEMAN. Os ths\nEpiscopal Church.\nRABBI ABRAM SIMON. Washington\nHebrew Congregation.\nDR. ANDREW R. BIRD, President.\nFederation of Churches.\nRIGHT REV. W. COLEMAN NEVILS,\nS. J., President, Georgetown Uni\nversity.\nDR